statement:
\emph{In this question you will state and then apply the Mean Value
Theorem.}

Use your answer in part
\href{Science:Math_Exam_Resources/Courses/MATH110/April_2011/Question_3_(b)}{(b)}
to explain why we may conclude that $\sin b \leq b$ for any positive
value \emph{b}.

sols:
In the previous question, we showed that for some $c$ in the interval
$(0,b)$

\begin{align*}\cos(c) = \frac{\sin(b)}{b}\end{align*}

Now we know that for all possible values of $c$, $\cos(c)$ is bounded
above by 1, or

\begin{align*}\cos(c) \leq 1\end{align*}

Substituting what we know from part (b), this is the same as

\begin{align*}\frac{\sin(b)}{b} \leq 1\end{align*}

Because $b > 0$ we can multiply both sides by \emph{b} to get

\begin{align*}\sin(b) \leq b\end{align*}

Which completes our proof.
